VALUES
(1, 5, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And Jared lived an hundred sixty and two years, and he begat Enoch:', 0, 67, 'connection', 'Generational Significance', 'The mention of Jared living 162 years and begetting Enoch connects to the broader theme of genealogies in Genesis, especially in Genesis 4:25-26, where the line of Seth is introduced. This lineage is significant as Enoch becomes a pivotal figure, known for his walk with God (Genesis 5:24), representing a faithful remnant amidst a lineage that often strayed from God. Understanding these connections helps us appreciate the narrative of God’s desire for relationship through successive generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 4:26", "description": "Introduces the descendants of Seth and the importance of worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And Jared lived an hundred sixty and two years, and he begat Enoch:', 0, 67, 'theology', 'Divine Timing in Generations', 'This verse emphasizes the theological concept of God''s sovereignty in the unfolding of history through generations. Many scholars believe that the ages and lifespans of these patriarchs demonstrate God''s providence and timing in preparing the world for redemption. Jared’s lifespan and the birth of Enoch illustrate the continuity of God’s plan and the importance of legacy in faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of genealogies in the context of God''s redemptive plan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'he begat Enoch:', 52, 67, 'question', 'Legacy of Faith', 'What does it mean for us today that Jared begat Enoch, a man noted for his unique relationship with God? How might we reflect on the legacies we are creating for future generations in our faith and practice? This prompts us to consider how our actions and faith influence those who come after us.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And Jared lived after he begat Enoch eight hundred years, and begat sons and daughters:', 0, 87, 'connection', 'Generational Faithfulness', 'Jared''s long life and fatherhood echo the theme of generational faithfulness seen in Genesis 17:7, where God establishes His covenant with Abraham and his descendants. This connection highlights the importance of lineage in God''s redemptive plan and emphasizes how each generation contributes to the unfolding of His purposes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:7", "description": "God''s covenant with Abraham and his descendants"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'after he begat Enoch eight hundred years, and begat sons and daughters:', 16, 87, 'theology', 'Longevity as Divine Favor', 'Many scholars believe that the extended lifespans in Genesis reflect God’s favor and the intended harmony of creation before the Fall. This perspective suggests that Jared''s long life allowed him significant opportunity to influence Enoch, who would become a pivotal figure in faith, indicating the importance of parental guidance in spiritual development.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'begat sons and daughters:', 62, 87, 'question', 'Understanding Legacy', 'What does it mean for us today to consider the legacy we leave through our children and their faith? How can we actively engage in nurturing their spiritual growth, just as Jared would have influenced Enoch and his siblings?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And Jared lived after he begat Enoch eight hundred years', 0, 56, 'greek', 'Life and Duration', 'Although the Old Testament is primarily in Hebrew, the concept of ''life'' here can be connected to the Hebrew word חַי (chai, H2416) – life, living, or being alive. This term underscores the significance of Jared''s extended life as a blessing and a testament to God''s sustaining hand throughout generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2416", "description": "Strong''s definition for ''life''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Jared were nine hundred sixty and two years: and he died.', 0, 77, 'connection', 'Longevity in Genesis', 'The mention of Jared''s lifespan connects to other figures in Genesis noted for their long lives, such as Methuselah (Genesis 5:27) and Noah (Genesis 9:29). These long lifespans illustrate the early human condition before the flood, which many scholars interpret as a reflection of the original creation''s vitality. Understanding these connections can deepen our appreciation of the narrative of human history in the biblical context.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:27", "description": "This verse highlights Methuselah''s lifespan, underscoring the theme of longevity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 65, 77, 'theology', 'The Certainty of Death', 'The phrase ''and he died'' serves as a sobering reminder of the inevitability of death, a theme that permeates Scripture. Many scholars believe this reflects the consequence of sin introduced in Genesis 3. This acknowledgment of mortality invites believers to consider the temporary nature of life and the hope of eternal life through Christ (John 3:16), emphasizing the need for spiritual readiness.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 3:19", "description": "This verse discusses the curse of death as a result of sin."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Jared', 20, 25, 'question', 'Understanding Lifespan', 'What significance does the long lifespan of Jared hold in the narrative of Genesis? How does knowing that he lived for over nine centuries affect our understanding of human history and God''s plan for humanity?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'all the days of Jared were nine hundred sixty and two years', 4, 63, 'greek', 'Days and Lifespan', 'יָמִים (yamim, H3117) - days; signifies the complete duration of life. The use of ''days'' here emphasizes not just the quantity of years but the fullness of time experienced by Jared, showcasing the biblical view that life is a series of divinely appointed days.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3117", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for days."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And Enoch lived sixty and five years, and begat Methuselah:', 0, 59, 'connection', 'Enoch''s Legacy', 'The mention of Enoch and his son Methuselah can be connected to Hebrews 11:5, which states that Enoch was taken away so that he did not see death. This connection highlights Enoch''s unique relationship with God, emphasizing his faith and righteousness. Methuselah, whose name means ''his death shall bring'', serves as a significant figure in the genealogical line leading to Noah, making Enoch''s legacy pivotal in biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 11:5", "description": "Highlighting Enoch''s faith and divine favor."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And Enoch lived sixty and five years, and begat Methuselah:', 0, 59, 'theology', 'Significance of Enoch''s Life', 'Many scholars believe that Enoch''s life, especially his close walk with God, illustrates the ideal relationship that believers are encouraged to pursue. His longevity of life (365 years) is often interpreted as a symbol of divine favor, suggesting that living in accordance with God''s will can lead to a spiritually enriched life. This passage encourages believers to reflect on their own walk with God.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of Enoch''s relationship with God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'begat Methuselah', 42, 58, 'question', 'Reflection on Fatherhood', 'What does it mean for Enoch to ''begat Methuselah'' in the context of legacy and spiritual influence? How can we apply the principles of fatherhood and mentorship seen in Enoch''s life to our relationships today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And Enoch lived sixty and five years', 0, 36, 'greek', 'Living in God''s Plan', 'חַי (chai, H2416) - life. The Hebrew term for life emphasizes vitality and purpose. Enoch''s life, marked by faithfulness, demonstrates the importance of living in alignment with God''s purpose, which is illustrated through his unique relationship with Him.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2416", "description": "Hebrew word for life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'walked with God', 10, 25, 'connection', 'Biblical Walking with God', 'The phrase ''walked with God'' is significant in Scripture, notably seen in Genesis 6:9 where Noah is described similarly. This connection emphasizes a close, personal relationship with the Divine. Furthermore, Micah 6:8 calls believers to walk humbly with God, suggesting that such a walk signifies active participation in a faithful relationship, which is foundational to biblical faith.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:9", "description": "Noah is described as a righteous man who walked with God."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Micah 6:8", "description": "Calls believers to walk humbly with God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'after he begat Methuselah', 26, 51, 'theology', 'Significance of Fatherhood', 'Many scholars believe that the mention of Enoch walking with God after the birth of Methuselah signifies a transformation in his life. Methuselah''s name, meaning ''his death shall bring'', suggests a prophetic link to the impending judgment of the Flood, thus highlighting the urgency and importance of Enoch''s relationship with God during a pivotal time in human history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of Enoch''s walk with God post-fatherhood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'walked with God', 10, 25, 'question', 'Personal Walk with God', 'What does it mean for you to ''walk with God'' in your daily life? Considering Enoch''s example, how might your relationship with God influence the way you live and make decisions today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'three hundred sixty and five years', 31, 65, 'connection', 'Significance of Lifespan', 'The lifespan of Enoch, ''three hundred sixty and five years,'' can be compared with Genesis 6:3, where God limits human lifespan to ''one hundred twenty years.'' This contrast highlights Enoch''s unique relationship with God, as he is taken without experiencing death. Understanding Enoch''s lifespan encourages reflection on the divine purpose in human longevity and the call to walk closely with God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "God''s declaration on human lifespan"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'three hundred sixty and five years', 31, 65, 'theology', 'Divine Timeframe', 'Many scholars believe that the specific number ''three hundred sixty-five'' can symbolize completeness in the context of God''s creation. The year consists of 365 days, which may suggest that Enoch''s life was complete in God''s eyes, representing a full cycle of time spent in faithful communion with Him. This view encourages believers to consider how they spend their time in relation to their spiritual walk.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Enoch were three hundred sixty and five years:', 0, 66, 'question', 'Life''s Purpose Reflection', 'What does the brevity of Enoch''s life, culminating in ''three hundred sixty and five years,'' reveal about the importance of living purposefully? How can we ensure that our days are marked by a deeper relationship with God, as Enoch''s was?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And', 0, 3, 'greek', 'Walking with God', 'הלך (halak, H1980) - to walk, go, or come. This Hebrew term emphasizes not just physical movement but a lifestyle of obedience and companionship with God. Enoch''s walk with God indicates a continuous, intimate relationship that transcends mere ritual, serving as a model for believers today.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1980", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And Enoch walked with God:', 0, 26, 'connection', 'Walking with God', 'Enoch''s relationship with God mirrors that of Noah, described in Genesis 6:9 as ''Noah walked with God.'' Both figures exemplify a life of faithfulness and communion with the divine. This connection is significant as it highlights a consistent biblical theme of righteousness amidst a corrupt world, showing that God seeks fellowship with those who strive to live in accordance with His will.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:9", "description": "Noah''s righteousness and relationship with God"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'and he was not;', 27, 42, 'theology', 'The Mystery of Enoch''s Departure', 'Many scholars believe that Enoch being ''not'' signifies a unique divine intervention, where he was taken by God without experiencing death. This event prefigures the New Testament concept of being ''caught up'' as seen in 1 Thessalonians 4:17. It presents a profound theological insight into God''s sovereignty over life and death and foreshadows the hope of eternal life for believers.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 4:17", "description": "Paul''s teaching on the rapture"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'for God took him.', 43, 60, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Intervention', 'What does it mean for God to ''take'' Enoch? How does this concept shape our understanding of God''s authority over life and His plans for humanity? Reflecting on this can deepen our appreciation for God''s intimate involvement in the lives of His faithful followers and the hope we have in His promises.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'And Methuselah lived an hundred eighty and seven years, and begat Lamech:', 0, 73, 'connection', 'Methuselah''s Longevity', 'Methuselah is noted for his extraordinary lifespan of 969 years (Genesis 5:27), which is the longest recorded in the Bible. This connection emphasizes the theme of longevity in the antediluvian period, reflecting the biblical view of life before the flood. Additionally, his name is often interpreted as ''his death shall bring,'' which can be seen as a prophetic statement leading to the flood, aligning with the narrative in Genesis 6:5-7 about the wickedness of humanity that prompted God''s decision.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:5-7", "description": "Describes the wickedness of man leading to the flood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'begat Lamech', 60, 72, 'theology', 'Significance of Lineage', 'The phrase ''begat Lamech'' signifies the importance of lineage in biblical narratives. Many scholars believe that genealogies serve to connect key figures in salvation history. Lamech, as Methuselah''s son, plays a pivotal role in the lineage leading to Noah, through whom the promise of God''s covenant post-flood is established. This highlights God''s faithfulness through generations, underscoring the theological concept of covenantal succession.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the importance of genealogies in the Bible."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'an hundred eighty and seven years', 21, 54, 'question', 'Reflecting on Lifespan', 'What does Methuselah''s age of 187 years reflect about the value of life and time? In a world where lifespan is often seen as a measure of success or achievement, how can we apply the lessons of longevity and purpose from biblical figures like Methuselah to our own lives? How can we ensure that our years are filled with significance in our walk with God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'after he begat Lamech seven hundred eighty and two years', 21, 77, 'connection', 'Lamech and Generations', 'The mention of Lamech here connects to Genesis 4:18, where Lamech is noted as a descendant of Cain. This relationship highlights the evolving lineage from Adam through Seth and Cain, underscoring the theme of human generations and their significance in biblical history. It invites reflection on the legacy of each line, particularly as the narrative progresses towards Noah.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 4:18", "description": "Lamech''s lineage and its implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'and begat sons and daughters:', 79, 108, 'theology', 'God''s Command to Multiply', 'This phrase reflects the theological concept of procreation as a divine command, echoing Genesis 1:28 where God instructs humanity to be fruitful and multiply. Many scholars believe that the mention of Methuselah''s descendants emphasizes God''s ongoing covenant relationship with humanity, as each generation contributes to the unfolding of God''s plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God''s command to multiply."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Methuselah lived after he begat Lamech', 4, 42, 'question', 'Legacy and Longevity', 'What does Methuselah’s long life teach us about patience and faithfulness in God''s timing? His extended years serve as a reminder of God''s mercy and grace, inviting us to consider how we live our lives in light of our own legacies.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'seven hundred eighty and two years', 43, 77, 'greek', 'Years of Methuselah', 'שבע מאות ושמונים ושניים (sheva me''ot u''shmoneh u''shnayim, H7657) - ''seven hundred and eighty and two''. The numerical values in the Hebrew text convey a sense of completeness and divine order. Methuselah''s age can be seen as a metaphor for the fullness of life and God''s providence over generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7657", "description": "Strong''s number for ''seven'' in the context of age."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Methuselah were nine hundred sixty and nine years: and he died.', 0, 83, 'connection', 'Lifespan Comparisons', 'Methuselah''s lifespan of 969 years is the longest recorded in the Bible, which emphasizes the longevity of antediluvian patriarchs. This can be compared to Genesis 6:3, where God limits human lifespan to 120 years, indicating a significant shift in human conditions post-flood. Understanding these contrasts highlights the impact of sin and divine judgment on humanity''s longevity and relationship with God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "God''s limit on human lifespan after the flood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Methuselah were nine hundred sixty and nine years: and he died.', 0, 83, 'theology', 'The Nature of Death', 'This passage reflects the inevitability of death as a consequence of sin, a theme prevalent throughout Scripture. Romans 5:12 states, ''Therefore, just as sin entered the world through one man, and death through sin, and in this way death came to all people, because all sinned.'' Methuselah''s death signifies the fulfillment of God''s judgment and serves as a reminder of mortality in a fallen world.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 5:12", "description": "Death as a consequence of sin."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 71, 83, 'question', 'Reflecting on Mortality', 'What does Methuselah''s death teach us about the human condition and our own mortality? How does recognizing the finite nature of life influence our priorities and our relationship with God? Consider how the legacy we leave behind can reflect our faith and values.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'nine hundred sixty and nine years', 36, 69, 'greek', 'Significance of Numbers', 'Although the text is in Hebrew, the number ''nine'' (תשע, tesha, H8337) symbolizes completeness and divine order, reflecting God''s design in creation. Methuselah''s long life can be seen as an extension of God''s patience and grace before the impending flood.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8337", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''nine''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'And Lamech lived an hundred eighty and two years, and begat a son:', 0, 66, 'connection', 'Lamech''s Lineage', 'Lamech, as a descendant of Adam, continues the lineage that is significant in biblical history. Cross-referencing with Genesis 4:25-26 shows the continuation of the godly line through Seth, contrasting with the ungodly line of Cain. This connection emphasizes the importance of lineage in God''s plan for redemption.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 4:25-26", "description": "Highlights the lineage of Seth from whom Lamech descends."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'And Lamech lived an hundred eighty and two years, and begat a son:', 0, 66, 'theology', 'Significance of Lamech''s Age', 'Many scholars believe that the age at which Lamech fathered Noah (182 years) symbolizes a pivotal point in history, indicating God''s grace in the midst of increasing wickedness. This age also serves to foreshadow the coming judgment through the flood, as Noah will later become the vessel of salvation for mankind.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of Lamech''s age and Noah''s birth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'And Lamech lived an hundred eighty and two years, and begat a son:', 0, 66, 'question', 'Reflecting on Generational Impact', 'What does it mean for us today to recognize the significance of generational impacts in our families and communities? How does Lamech''s decision to name his son Noah reflect his hope for future restoration amidst hardship?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'And Lamech lived an hundred eighty and two years, and begat a son:', 0, 66, 'greek', 'Understanding ''begat''', 'Although this passage is primarily in Hebrew, understanding the concept of ''begat'' (translated from H3205, יָלַד - yalad) is crucial as it signifies not just birth but continuation of a legacy and covenantal promise. This term underlines the importance of lineage in biblical narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "The Hebrew term for ''to bear, bring forth, beget''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'This same shall comfort us concerning our work and toil of our hands,', 37, 106, 'connection', 'Comfort in Labor', 'Lamech''s reference to Noah as a source of comfort relates to Genesis 3:17-19, where God curses the ground because of Adam''s sin, causing toil in work. This connection emphasizes the hope tied to Noah''s future role in God''s plan, which ultimately leads to restoration after the flood. The theme of finding comfort amidst labor resonates throughout Scripture, pointing to God''s faithfulness even in our struggles.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 3:17-19", "description": "God''s curse on the ground and the toil of work"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'because of the ground which the Lord hath cursed.', 107, 156, 'theology', 'The Curse and Redemption', 'This passage highlights the theological concept of sin''s consequences. The curse upon the ground symbolizes the brokenness in creation and the need for redemption. Many scholars believe that Noah''s name signifies a turning point, foreshadowing the eventual renewal of creation through God''s covenant with humanity after the flood, reflecting God''s mercy in the face of judgment.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on the significance of Noah''s name in redemption"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'And he called his name Noah,', 0, 28, 'question', 'Meaning of Comfort', 'What does it mean for us today to find comfort in the name ''Noah''? As Lamech associates Noah with comfort, how can we relate this to Christ, who offers ultimate comfort and rest? In what ways are we called to bring hope and relief to those burdened by the effects of sin and toil in their lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'And Lamech lived after he begat Noah five hundred ninety and five years, and begat sons and daughters:', 0, 102, 'connection', 'Lamech''s Longevity', 'Lamech''s lifespan can be compared to that of his ancestors, particularly Adam, who lived 930 years (Genesis 5:5), and Methuselah, who lived 969 years (Genesis 5:27). This connection highlights the decreasing lifespans of humanity post-Fall, illustrating the impact of sin on creation. It invites reflection on the nature of life and longevity in the biblical narrative.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:5", "description": "Adam''s lifespan"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:27", "description": "Methuselah''s lifespan"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'And Lamech lived after he begat Noah five hundred ninety and five years, and begat sons and daughters:', 0, 102, 'theology', 'Generational Legacy', 'This passage suggests a theological emphasis on generational legacy and the continuation of humanity. Lamech not only lived many years but also fathered multiple children, which signifies the importance of family and the passing down of faith and values. Many scholars believe that this reflects God''s covenantal faithfulness in continuing humanity despite sin.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'after he begat Noah', 17, 36, 'question', 'Meaning of ''Begat''', 'What does it signify for Lamech to have continued to live and father children after Noah''s birth? How does this relate to the hope Lamech expressed in Noah as a comfort against the cursed ground? Reflecting on this can deepen our understanding of God''s plan through generations.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Lamech were seven hundred seventy and seven years: and he died.', 0, 83, 'connection', 'Lamech''s Lifespan in Context', 'Lamech''s lifespan of 777 years echoes the significance of numbers in Scripture, particularly the use of seven as a symbol of completeness (Genesis 2:2-3). This connection highlights the theological depth of Lamech''s life, suggesting a completeness in his time before the flood, preparing for the new beginning with Noah. Additionally, it mirrors the genealogical patterns established in Genesis, emphasizing the continuity of God''s plan through generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 2:2-3", "description": "God rests on the seventh day, establishing the significance of the number seven."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Lamech were seven hundred seventy and seven years: and he died.', 0, 83, 'theology', 'Human Mortality', 'The phrase ''and he died'' serves as a sobering reminder of human mortality, a theme that resonates throughout the Scriptures. Many scholars believe this underscores the reality of sin entering the world and its consequences, as seen in Romans 5:12, where death came through sin. Thus, Lamech''s death signifies not just an end, but also the continuation of the human condition affected by the fall.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 5:12", "description": "Death entered the world through sin, relating to the mortality of all humans."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 71, 83, 'question', 'Reflection on Death''s Finality', 'What does Lamech''s death teach us about the inevitability of mortality? In a world often distracted by the pursuit of life and success, how does acknowledging the reality of death inform our understanding of purpose and legacy? This prompts reflection on how we live our lives in light of eternity.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'seven hundred seventy and seven years', 32, 69, 'greek', 'Symbolism of Seven', 'שִׁבְעָה (shiv''ah, H7651) - seven. The number seven is often associated with divine perfection and completion in Hebrew tradition, as seen in creation narratives. Lamech''s age, being a multiple of seven, could symbolize a fulfillment of his life’s purpose and readiness for the transition to a new covenant through Noah.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7651", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''seven''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');